#troubleshootingphysicalhardware

April 22, 2026

You cannot fix a network if the machine itself won't turn on. Having built a strong foundation in command-line diagnostics, I am stepping away from the terminal for this log 
to focus entirely on the physical side of IT: diagnosing, troubleshooting, and repairing Physical Hardware.

CORE INTERNAL COMPONENTS
  1. CPU (Central Processing Unit): The CPU is one of the most integral pieces to the build and often has the same issues occur, typically involving: Heat, Power, and Contact.

    HEAT: Modern CPUs have safety measures built into them called 'Thermal Throttling' that intentionally slows it down to generate less heat after reaching a certain temperature 
    (Typically between 90-100 degrees Celsius or 194-212 degrees Farenheit). If the CPU hits its T-Junction limit, it will shut down automatically to avoid melting.
      TROUBLESHOOTING: If the PC shuts down, touch the heat sink. If it's cold but the CPU is reporting high temperaturess, the heat isn't transferring (bad paste). If it’s burning 
      hot, the fan is failing or the airflow is blocked.

    POWER: Troubleshooting CPU power usually involves checking the dedicated electrical path from the PSU to the Motherboard VRMs (Voltage Regulator Modules).
      TROUBLESHOOTING: The EPS 12V Connector: Most modern CPUs require a dedicated 4-pin or 8-pin (4+4) power cable plugged into the top-left of the motherboard. Without this, the 
      system will often spin its fans but never display an image. In the CPU socket, specific pins are dedicated solely to power and grounding. If these are bent or dirty, the CPU 
      may receive inconsistent voltage, leading to "random" shutdowns that are hard to replicate.

    CONTACT: Pins are on the motherboard. They are extremely fragile. One bent pin can prevent the "memory controller" from seeing your RAM or stop the PC from booting entirely. 
      TROUBLESHOOTING: Every CPU has a small gold triangle in one corner. This must line up with the triangle on the socket. Misalignment leads to crushed pins and permanent 
      hardware death.
    

  2. RAM (Random Access Memory): Troubleshooting RAM issues typically come by focusing on physical seating, memory corruption, compatibility and speed issues. RAM is often a culprit 
  in "ghost" issues that appear and disappear without warning.

    PHYSICAL CONNECTION: RAM sticks can slide out of their slots over time due to heat expansion or vibration which will cause POST to fail.
      TROUBLESHOOTING: RAM requires pressure in order to snap correctly into place. If it hasn't snapped into place it may be only making partial contact which can cause 
      intermittent crashes. Most motherboards have four slots. To run in "Dual-Channel" (for better performance), sticks usually need to be in slots 2 and 4 (or 1 and 3). Check the 
      motherboard manual; placing them side-by-side often causes stability issues. Sometimes the RAM is fine, but the motherboard slot is dead.
    
    MEMORY CORRUPTION: Oftem when a BSOD (Blue Screen Of Death) occurs on a computer, it may potentially be from internal chips failing within the RAM. These internal failures
    are usually caused by static discharge (ESD) during installation or sometimes age will wear it down over time. Specific errors that will notify you of RAM issues will be
    messages such as: 
    -MEMORY_MANAGEMENT
    -PAGE_FAULT_IN_NONPAGED_AREA
    -CRITICAL_PROCESS_DIED
      TROUBLESHOOTING: One can run Windows Memory Diagnostic and check for any errors that show up on the blue-screen test. If messages do appear, then the RAM is physically failing
      and it'd be best to physically check if the RAM has any static/dust buildup. After removing the RAM you can clean it with 90% Isopropyl Alcohol.

    COMPATABILITY & SPEED ISSUES: Mixing and matching different RAM sticks can certainly work, the issue with is that all of the sticks of RAM will be forced to work at the same
    speed as that of the slowest stick. This can cause the PC to refuse to bootup because the RAM sticks are fighting with each other about the speeds in which to operate.
      TROUBLESHOOTING: If you just added new RAM and the PC won't boot, clear the CMOS (pull the battery for 30 seconds). This resets the RAM settings to "Auto" so it can try to find 
      a stable speed for the new sticks.
    

  3. STORAGE (SSD/HDD): Typically storage will have issues with physical connectivity, mechanical degradation, and logical errors. 
    
    PHYSICAL CONNECTIVITY: You will know this is the issue if the driver doesn't appear at all in the BIOS/UEFI. You won't feel the HDD vibration, and for SSD the system will act
    as though the slot is completely empty. 
      TROUBLESHOOTING: Typically SATA (Serial Advanced Technology Attachment) cables fail more often than the drivers themselves so it's a good idea to check if something is wrong 
      with this cable. Replace the SATA cable with a new one or try moving the power connector to a different plug to make sure it isn't a dead power issue.

    MECHANICAL DEGRADATION: With HDD If you hear the "Click of Death" which is essentially just a rhythmic clicking/grinding noise stop using the system. With SSD the drive becomes
    read only and only allows you to read files, not save anything new to the driver, or also it can just stop working during a large file write.
      TROUBLESHOOTING: Use a utility like CrystalDiskInfo to read the drive's internal health report. Look for "Reallocated Sectors Count." If this number is high, the drive is 
      physically dying. Hold the drive. If you feel a smooth hum, the motor is fine. If it’s jerking or silent, the mechanical components are seized. Check temperatures. If an NVMe 
      SSD exceeds 70°C, it may disconnect itself to prevent heat damage. Ensure the thermal pad is making contact with the heatsink.

    LOGICAL & FILE SYSTEM ERRORS: You know this is the issue when the driver shows up in the BIOS but Windows won't boot up. Anoher issue that may come up is errors such as "File
    System Error" pop-ups or even a BSOD with a message saying: INACCESSIBLE_BOOT_DEVICE  
      TROUBLESHOOTING: To fix this you can run the "chkdsk" command in which this forces Windows to find any "bad blocks" of data and mark them as 'unusuable' to potentially save
      the rest of the data. You can also check the File System to see if the driver is missing, in which case you go to Disk Management and check if the drive is listed "Unallocated"
      or "Foreign"; Chances are you just need to assign it to a drive letter. If the drive is healthy but won't boot up, you can use a Windows Recovery USB to run a Boot Record 
      command to repair the software instructions that start the OS.


  4. MOTHERBOARD: Symptoms of a motherboard not functioning properly can be things such as a PC being dead (not turning on any lights nor fans, etc.), the screen turns on but gets
  stuck on the logo, or specific parts of the board stop working such as USB ports on the back, etc. These are caused by issues in Electrical/Physical Integrity, Firmware & Config.,
  and Communication/Port Failure.

    ELECTRICAL/PHYSICAL INTEGRITY: The symptoms of this would be that the PC is completely dead in that lights aren't working, random shut-offs occur, or a burnt plastic smell.
      TROUBLESHOOTING: To see if this is realy the issue you can look at the motherboard to see if there are issues with any capacitors (bulging at the top, popped, leaking). If
        there are any of these issues then the board is electrically unstable and the it must be replaced. Another factor that may cause issues is ensuring the motherboard is mounted 
        on brass standoffs. If the back of the motherboard touches the metal computer case directly, it creates a "short circuit" that prevents the PC from turning on.

    FIRMWARE & CONFIGURATION (BIOS/UEFI): Symptoms of this would be the PC turning on but it keeps getting stuck on the logo screen or forgets the time and date anytime you unplug it.
    It also can fail to recognize new hardware like CPUs or GPUs.
      TROUBLESHOOTING:


POWER AND BOOT DIAGNOSTICS
  POWER SUPPLY UNIT (PSU)

  POST (POWER ON SELF-TEST)

EXTERNAL PORTS AND CABLES
  VIDEO CONNECTIONS

  PERIPHERAL PORTS

  NETWORK (RJ-45 ETHERNET PORT)

TECHNICIAN TOOLKIT AND SAFETY
  ESD (ELECTROSTATIC DISCHARGE)
